A '''migraine''' is a medical condition which usually causes a pounding, throbbing headache on one side of the head. The pain may be very bad and hurt so much that a person may have a hard time doing anything. While most people who have migraines get a headache, not everyone does. There are different kinds of migraines and some do not cause a headache but do have other [[Signs and symptoms (medicine)|symptoms]].
 
Most migraines cause a headache and [[nausea]] and might make the person dizzy or very sensitive to bright lights or loud noises. Some people have "auras" before a migraine starts, which means their eyesight becomes different. They may see funny patterns, have blurry vision, or may not be able to see at all. Other [[senses]] can change before or during a migraine, and the person may sense funny smells or tastes. Migraines can last a long time. Most migraines only last about 4 hours. Some can last up to 72 hours.

Migraines have been classified, based on how often they occur in a month: If a person has a headache for less than fifteen days, the migraine is called ''episodic migraine'' (EM), otherwise it is called ''chronic migraine'' (CM). Chronic means it happens over a long period of time. A certain amount of people who start off getting episodic migraines may start to get ''chronic migraines'' after a period of time. Chronic migraine then may ''revert'' or go back to episodic migraine. 

The exact causes of migraines are not known for sure. It was previously believed that the main cause of migraines were abnormalities in the vascular system in the brain. However, research suggests that the migraines start with a disorder in the central nervous system. When this disorder is triggered by various factors it sets off a cascade of neurological and biochemical reactions. Amongst these are reactions that affect the ''trigeminal nerve'' - which is the largest nerve in the head (cranial nerve) and the blood vessels (vascular system) which supply blood to the brain.   

There are different [[Factor (medicine)|risk factors]] which make a person more likely to have migraines. Being a female is itself a risk factor as is a history of migraines in family members. For a person who has migraines there are different trigger factors which may set off a migraine attack. In a large group of females who have migraines one of the main trigger factors is when the amount of the hormone ''estrogen'' in their body is either drops too low or the amount ''fluctuates'' (goes up and down).

According to statistics collected by the World Health Organization, it's been estimated that migraine headache is the most expensive brain disorder in terms of treatment and disability in the [[European Union]] and the [[United States]].<ref>[http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs277/en/ World Health Organisation Factsheet No 277]. Headache disorders. Published March 2004. Accessed December 19, 2012.</ref>
