'''[[Aura (symptom)|Aura]]''' (from the Greek word for breeze) is the word used to describe a series of [[neurology|neurological]] symptoms that may begin before an [[epilepsy|epileptic seizure]] or a migraine headache. About 15% of people who have a migraine will have the kind with an aura. The symptoms may include visual problems such as ''scotomas'' (losing vision for a short time, seeing zig-zag lines or floating spots etc.), [[vertigo]], a ringing noise in the ears (tinnitus) and problems speaking.<ref>Robert A. Davidoff: ''Migraine: Manifestations, Pathogenesis, and Management:(Contemporary Neurology Series) Second Edition'' pp. 49-51 (Oxford University Press, 2002) ISBN 0195137051</ref>
