==History==
Symptoms that mimic those of migraines have been recorded in various cultures throughout written history. The first known mention was found on [[cuneiform]] [[tablet]]s from Babylonia dating to 2000-1880 B.C.E.<ref>Richard Grossinger:Migraine Auras: When the Visual World Fails. North Atlantic Books, 2006; p.43 ISBN 155643619X</ref>A treatment for migraine can be found in the ''Ebers Papyrus'', an Ancient Egyptian medical text named after George Ebers, the  German Eygptologist who discovered them. In the ancient text dated to 1552 B.C.E. migraine is refereed to as "suffering in half the head". <ref>John F. Nunn: Ancient Egyptian Medicine University of Oklahoma Press, 2002 p.93 ISBN 0806135042</ref>
